segments.text: It's November the 13th, Friday, and I am visiting with Dr. Jack Campbell, who has been in the Department of Curriculum and Instruction since 1970.

And Dr. Campbell is going to share a few of his thoughts and perceptions about the changes that have occurred at Texas A&M since he arrived, perhaps something about what might have caused some of these great changes and how it has affected
the growth of the college.
And do you have a particular change or a series of changes that have occurred that stand out as the most important?
I think if I could just
point out some of the things as I've gone back over my notes that maybe some of which you can use later on.
The most important changes I may not be in a position to know, but I've learned about Texas A&M and the need for a professor of foundations at the
Annual meeting in Chicago, 1970, February 28th and 29th.
I was attending the History of Education Society, John Dewey Society, and saw the flyer, which I believe I have given you.
And I was surprised.
Excuse me.
At the convention in February.
I believe I have given you a copy of it.
I have a copy, yes.
Earl Jones was associate to Dean Hill.
Glenn Johnson was the chairman of the PDCI.
Paul Hensarling was with the Ed Ed department and I think had, at one time, been a candidate for dean.

Let's see, as I moved into the university, the first one, the first big committees I was on was the Rutter Lecture Committee, which was a series of lectures to honor the president who died shortly before I arrived at Texas A&M.
He was in the hospital.
I had some notes, but by the time I arrived for the August
beginning of the 1970s session.
On this committee, there were a number of people.
I remember Professor Chalk, especially, with economics.
And I can go back and find that material if you are interested in the first lecture.
I'm interested in everything right now, Dr. Campbell, because everything has so many
tie-ins to a lot of the other things that I'm hearing.
And then again, everybody saw everything from different viewpoints.
And of course, it illustrates the interaction with other parts of the committee.
Our first speaker was Jacques Barzun, the former president of Columbia.
Did you say these lectures were in honor of the president's brother?
Yes.
We only had two of them, and then it just died out.
But Bar-Zoon, if we were going to pay, I think we were going to pay them something like $10,000 for a series of lectures, and then we would publish them.
The Bar-Zoon, Jacques Bar-Zoon, he has noticed he's called the Cultural History of Columbia Observation Saturday on the third final session of the lecture.
Are these to talk about Rutter himself?
No, nothing to do with Rutter.
His lecture was on manners, on the history of manners.
However, he never sent us the manuscript.
It's also an interesting anecdote-wise that our president at this time was our new president, Williams.
And Barzun never flew.
So he was coming by train, and we were all in the auditorium waiting for his lecture, and he hadn't arrived yet.
His train was stuck somewhere in Waco.
And I was sitting with President Williams, and Mr. Eskel Monroe got in his car and had driven me to Waco.
We had Barzun somewhere between here and there.
Well, Williams was regaling the audience.
But Barzun finally came.
That was his first of three lectures.
The series was on manners.
The committee.
came through with a second letter lecture the following year.
Of course, now this is April of 1972.
In 1972, it was also important because we established the chapter of Kappa Delta Pi, which was the honorary society in education that included women.
Kappa Delta Pi.
Kappa Delta Pi.
I'll make a copy of this, which gives you the names of the first people.
I had long been a member of that society and was one of the installing officers for the initiation team.
At that time, Frank Huber was also initiated into Kappa Delta Pi first.
Is that still in?
Is that an active chapter?
Yes, that is still active.
It's more or less serving our undergraduates now because Phi Delta Kappa has now admitted women.
But in 1972, it did not.
And as a new college of education, we had mostly women.
A little anecdote wise, I asked one of the corps members one time, how many corps members were in my education classes?
And they said they wanted to see what girls looked like.
Anyway, we had the monopoly on girls.
Oh, that's cute.
So we established Kappa Delta Phi.
We also had a civilian student council at that time, which was .
I was also appointed in 1972 by President William A. Centineo
committee, and a little bit later for the centennial committee for the diversity.
What were the duties in that committee?
Well, in the bicentennial committee, we never really did a lot.
But with the centennial committee, we made arrangements to develop that film.
that certain spirit or whatever, I forgot what it was.
We also got Hill to do the carvings.
That was one of the things our committee did.
And we arranged for countless lectures.
The 1976 lecture that I was mainly responsible for was when R. Freeman Butts, who was a leader in the history of education and was the co-chairman of my doctorate,
I came here from Columbia to speak.
I had to check on this, but I was active in the Texas Association of College Teachers since coming here.
I was twice president.
I was president at the centennial.
I think I was president again when the Senate was developed.
Texas Association of College Teachers spoke for officers and administrators in Austin.
President Miller was inaugurated.
I was a host of that.
I can't remember.
I remember that.
I was here for that one.
I do remember.
Miller's?
There was one.
That escapes me.
And Miller was also the only person, to my knowledge, who joined TACT.
Mr. Campbell, when were the women admitted to Phi Delta Kappa, and was that a local decision, or was it the national association?
It was a national, and it came as a result of court cases.
I think you can confirm that.
And Mark, in our department, is the president this year.
I was just initiated into it last Monday night.
Oh, well, I just don't have time because I have three night classes, and by Thursday I'm so tired I can hardly think of going up.
But back in the early 70s, you see, the women had that.
Don't wait.
I really think Kappa Delta Pi, it's just as old as Phi Delta Kappa, and in my way of thinking, it was a greater...
organization that had admitted first honor societies to blacks and women, and that was an honorary member.

When we look at all of these things that were happening back when you just first got here in the 70s, and you were instrumental in working very actively in a lot of committees, the mission of the college was still the same as it is now, or as it was for any land grant university, not just the College of Education.
But teaching, research, and service have been the focal point.
Has that changed, or has the emphasis changed on those, in your perception, within this college?
like more pressure or more emphasis on research versus teaching or survey.
No different departments concentrate more on one.
I think that under Dean Buber, that as far as tenure and promotion is concerned, the stress was on publication, which

It's easy to measure, and of course it gives national knowledge, and that was important, because teachers came here, even in Texas, nobody knew that they were going to be taught with a parent-teacher.
That was probably the biggest supplier and most respected supplier of teachers.
So we had to get visibility.
How can I document that about it being the most respected supplier of teachers?
I know I've heard it a couple of times.
Well, I think you can.
the best place to find out first how many you're producing.
And it's possible that TEA would be the best source there for how many we're producing.
I think you're also maybe even leading the nation in math and science.
That's what I heard.
But this is just hearsay, of course.
I'm more conscious of the now, you know, since visiting with you, about verifying, you know, historically some of these things, and that's the thing that I'm not sure.
Of course, I don't see this as much historical as an oral history.
It is.
So when somebody else can use this data for what it might be worth in terms of...
So it's not absolutely essential that I have, if I say something like what you just said,
I don't have to, you know, come back and triangulate in such a way that it's verified right here that we do produce the most or that... Well, you can say that I said that.
Now, I may be wrong.
Well, whoever, several other people have said it, and I've seen it, and I've heard the dean say it at meetings.
Our memories are tricky.
You're not... Oh, sure.
And that's why we need to, just like in our income tax, we have to keep records.
And, but...

I would say that Dean Corrigan's style is quite different and feels that the worth of a person should be considered, not just publication, so that we could put someone forward for them as a distinguished publication list as we used to.
What is this person's contributions and
get along without this person, and that's sort of the criteria.
There still is a penalty, so to speak, for not publishing.
I know I had at least one person say that they have paid the price by not getting a full professorship because they have not published, even though they've been here for 30 years.
Yes, you see, the publication record is the easiest thing to measure, and it's the one thing that
Well, what about service, though?
I'm seeing a lot of visibility on the people that are out there working with, you know,
things like the principal center, all those different conferences.
I'm happy because that's where I've been.
But doesn't that also provide a lot of visibility for the college?
What kind of service do you mean?
Well, like going out into the educational field and doing some collaborative.
I guess maybe that's part of, is it part of service or part of teaching?
Yes, yes it is.
And I think, here for instance, I have a few things in the folder.
I used to, when I, this is 1973, have students go out to the
the girls club, the boys club, child development centers, and contribute their time.
This was before we had a lot of field services.
Now, of course, this is done to a greater extent.
How did that change?
It helped the community.
Sure.
It really got the community involved.
The field service activities, and I know they have changed, but when did they start changing?
Because I know teachers would never even get in the classroom.
We didn't until it was time for student teaching after we'd already been three or four years in school.
That's why I taught the foundation courses.
I'd get them at the beginning and I would make arrangements.
I couldn't get them into public schools very easily.
It was very complicated to get them into observe.
And so I got them into the girls club, the boys club, all the various church education.
Is it easier now to get into the public schools?
Oh, yes.
We have someone who's in charge of that.
But they didn't have that when I started here in the early 70s.
And in order to get them into the school, I would have to make rather detailed arrangements and then sometimes relationships.
Who's in charge of that kind of activity?
Tim Blair.
He's student teacher.
Yeah, that's the field experience.
Oh, I see.
We get people out earlier now.
But it was a big administrative position.
And while I was teaching classes, I couldn't do that so well.
And it was not good to give weeks in advance.
But if they were contributing to the girls club, the boys club,
some of these time going on a regular basis.
It wasn't as bad if they didn't show up sometime.

In this work that you did, like these things with students, Dr. Campbell, what about because of the growth of the college, has that affected your ability to, not your ability, but how you're able to work and interact with students just because of the sheer numbers?
Oh, I don't really feel that way at all.
A&M has been remarkable.
I've never been anywhere that, especially with students, from my own doctoral experience, very self-determining.
One of the things that Dean Hubert had, which still I bet was this, you had to be here after you were here, whereas I taught at Brooklyn very often,
faculty came in for their classes and maybe one or two hours of office.
Is that a policy of the college, or does it go by department?
Or is it an understood thing?
It's not just... Well, I think it came with the Corps and with the military.
I mean, even now, when you say that the faculty are expected to be, are normally here, is it, are you told by the department?
No, no, no.
It's just sort of a habit.
I even feel a little bit guilty if I go to the dentist.
Because you're used to being there.
So we do have a lot of time.
As always, though, students very often hesitate to come in.
We have this mentor service.
It's voluntary, is it not?
It's voluntary.
Are you one of the mentors?
Yes, but I just started this year, and I haven't had a single mentoree.
OK, but that's interesting.
How many graduate students committees do you serve on average?
I would say 50.
And I think I'm just well over-subscribed.
And the last couple of years, I've been trying to cut back, because I do not share very many, because people do not do historical dissertations.
But since I teach the foundations, I get them early.
I don't want to do historical visitations.
They're hard.
They're very time-consuming.
Now, we've talked about the different things that have affected the different changes and so forth.
How do you see the college now versus at the beginning?
as it is viewed by others or by outsiders.
I've had some strong comments about, you know, not a put down necessarily, but that the College of Education was
I don't know what you mean.
Oh, I see what you mean.
How do people view the college, and how has that changed?
When I first came here, I was quite delighted, because it seemed that education was respected.
Of course, that's very unusual.
You had the respect of all of the colleges.
And I think that Corrigan has the respect of everyone who knows him.
I think the problem with education and its respect is that, historically, there's been a profession for slaves.
The politicians themselves have not been happy about it.
It took a long time for them to accept the lawyers as optional workers for expanding the mind and so on.

but education is probably the most complex, and we don't have the hope, and I think we do make claims that we're a science, but my feeling is essentially we're doing the best we can, and I think there's been a lot of progress in expanding
several phases since I've been here.
When I came back to develop competency-based programs, that was the main point that we put everything to spell out the terminal behaviors, present a number of competencies.
Is that not the case now?
But we've been developing all of our courses on that.

And I can't remember the year, but it started to affect other parts of the university, where if we were going to produce history, we would also have to develop courses around competencies that was in education that you can't hit the other departments.
When you say you can't hit, who was doing the hitting?
Well, that was the state.
Oh, okay.
The state was, all of our programs had to be competency-based.
Now, the Attorney General, and this is a date you have to verify if you're interested.
Thank you.
I had a great deal to do with this, how to teach, professions, how to teach.
And after that settled down, and right now, of course, we're involved in completely dismantling.
the climate or the, you know, within this department, because this is the department that will be the hardest hit, I'm assuming.
Yes, we are working on what might be superior programs if we can develop a five-year certification program.
Are you involved in this process?
No, I am not involved.
I'm on one service.
slightly active in one community, which is developing.
If we could get interdisciplinary majors to truly liberal arts, I think this would...
But we're working on a five-year plan, which the state may not approve of.
Oh, that'd be decided.
We have...
To get this new program online by January, the sheets are quite unreasonable as to say to dismantle and restructure a program that allows no more than 18 hours.
I think this will not include reading courses.
But that you would major in another field, it has put a great deal of pressure on us.
We've gone through before.
And survived.
And survived.
I think people are thinking very well of teachers, although I don't have undergraduate seminar.
Oh, okay.
I do not teach students.
I just period people off.
And these will not really affect any of the graduate programs?
Not unless they abolish the major in education at all.
There is the possibility, you see, that...
It would be abolished completely.
I did some research on the history of, more or less chronicled the attitude of teachers in the ancient world.
And when you see they were, they isolated teachers.
They said, okay, when we start meeting teachers in public schools, we'll put them in normal
It's voice activated.
I guess I've been taking too much of your time.
No, it's voice activated.
No, that's fine.
No, we're doing great.

Anyway, we're in another phase here where I think that... A lot of changes, again, that we're looking at that are going to carry us perhaps, well, for sure, into the 20th or 21st century with possibly a whole new model.
It could be that we'll have a terrible teacher shortage.
I'm hearing that a lot.
And we already have one on the way, you know.
And also teacher retention, which is something that bothers me a lot, because maybe we're putting out all these teachers, but are they staying out there?
Well, I think the best ones aren't.
And the problem is, you're a conscientious person doing teacher education, but we're not reforming the schools.
I think it's immoral to take that kind of training.
And the people that will stay are the ones that are going to find the easiest way in class, so they don't have to talk to them.
Burnout.
I mean, of course, I'm not in the field, but you can't both be on that.
I think that if you're going to perform teacher education, you just can't perform teacher training.
I feel we can change the whole system.
But they have tried to reduce class size.
Yes.
Dr. Campbell, since you arrived at Texas A&M, because you've worked under two administrations, plus the interim in between, what are some of the highlights, maybe a highlight of each?
of each era.
I'm calling it an era because it was very distinct.
You know, half has been Dean Hubert within the life of the College of Education.
Now, this second half, which will be hitting 20 years pretty soon, is, you know, just a little bit about, you know, the highlights.
I also am going to ask you about, you know, your own contribution and what you feel the best about.
But you have a lot of insights and with your historical background, you know, your anecdotes are priceless.
But is there something that stands out?
Well, we've been on 12-month appointments from the beginning.
And we don't have the summer or semester, once in a while, talk of things.
Did you have sabbatical leave any time?
No, no.
No, I took the spring of 86 off without pay.
I was just worn out.
My brother died, and my mother needed a little bit of attention.
And I was just worn out.
It was probably kind of burnout, so I arranged to take the spring off.
So I, you know, it seems as though I've been involved
semester after semester, pretty much the same thing.
I always do my teaching differently.
I'm continuing revising what I'm doing, but I think I'm more like an enlisted man peeking over the top of the trench, and I don't see the whole picture.
So the administrators would be better to see the campaign.
I'm meeting the class that's going to do it.
We're all leaders to our campus.
It's a very exciting time.
I know you might say that we haven't trained.
I think that's the year I got to be a professor, too.
That would have been about six years after you arrived, right?
Yes.
Is that the average for our tenure?
I got tenured earlier, but I didn't get promoted at that time.
Now we usually have tenure and promotion at the same time.
The guy was tenured a few years earlier.
That's another thing that I was going to ask you about.
Interacting and collaborating with your colleagues or within departments or even outside of this department.
Do you have an opportunity to do very much of that?
Quite a bit.
I don't think there's as much as there used to be.
There's not as much there anymore because we're getting so big.
But our department is such a hard working department.
Glenn Johnson, his health broke down under the strain.
He had a heart attack under the strain.
this department do to people?
We knocked them off.
I think they worked very hard.
But there's so many certification programs, so much work to do.
We had David David temporarily.
He's been in our department ever since.
I think he came in 1980.
A typical choice.
Well, I was on one of the breakfast luncheons with Corbin.
I was trying to remember some of the other candidates.
One of them
I think I had known him because he was from Kentucky, and I knew him because he'd gotten the other two candidates we brought before him.
And I understand they were all pretty... All very good.
I can remember as a little anecdote why someone said, well, why don't we go to Maryland?
Well, that's not the same.
Oh, that's great.
Oh, another thing that might be of interest is that...
In 1982, I had proposed that we just have study abroad.
Donna Norton and I developed courses.
And Donna Norton got a grant from Conoco, which was lost.
And we had to get to the coordination board.
And believe it or not, there was the feeling
What can anybody learn?
The students were taken from here to go study there?
Yes, and we took 30 students in 1982 from the National Affairs.
It's changed so many times.
But they found this college very reasonable, and they had contacts.
So we got the foreign development here.
The study abroad.
and I think comparative education.
Was this the first department to initiate that?
Well, it's the first in education, as far as I know, and less agriculture.
The Ag Ed, of course, had extension programs.
There's been a lot of international work with other parts of college, but I know we have more courses in the summer.
I don't know if I asked you this earlier.
I'm in another conversation.
about how you felt that the college was achieving its mission on the teaching and research.
